# Workflow security discipline

- Pin every third-party action to a full 40-char commit SHA with a trailing `# vX.Y.Z`
  comment (Dependabot maintains both together). Tag or branch refs are findings, not style.
  The one sanctioned exception (SLSA generator, tag-required upstream) is documented in
  `docs/ci.md` and applies only to the disabled release workflow.
- Every workflow: top-level permissions of at most `contents: read`, explicit
  least-privilege per-job grants for anything beyond, `timeout-minutes` on every job,
  `concurrency` on every workflow, `persist-credentials: false` on every checkout.
- Never use `pull_request_target` or `workflow_run` triggers. Never interpolate
  untrusted event text (issue/PR titles or bodies, branch names, commit messages) into
  `run:` steps or prompts — pass values through `env:` indirection, and treat them as data.
- Benchmark/sandbox suites run on `workflow_dispatch` only; never add implicit triggers.
  Nightly, sandbox, and benchmark workflows set `cancel-in-progress: false`.
- The only status check a ruleset may require is the `ci-required` aggregator — never
  individual jobs (a skipped required check counts as passing; see docs/ci.md).
- Never weaken a gate to make it pass: no reducing Hypothesis case counts, no skipping
  checks, no `continue-on-error` on validation jobs, no editing zizmor/gitleaks config to
  silence a finding without a documented false-positive rationale.
- Caching: only hash-verified dependency download caches (e.g. uv). Never cache test
  databases, benchmark artifacts, `.hypothesis/`, or virtualenvs. Benchmark workflows are
  cache-free entirely.
- Secrets live only in owner-created environments (`sandbox`, `benchmark`), never
  repo-level; an absent secret evaluates to an empty string, so credentialed steps sit
  behind an explicit non-empty guard.
